Explanation: Main state budget bill.
BillPageText: House Bill 2 is traditionally the state's primary two-year appropriations bill, the vehicle the Legislature uses to set most of the state budget. More information about the budgeting process is available on the [Legislative Fiscal Division](https://leg.mt.gov/lfd/) website.

Explanation: Cuts Montana income taxes and expands the state Earned Income Tax Credit on a long-term basis.
Puts a portion of the state budget surplus to income tax rebates.
Raises threshold for tax-exempt business property from $300,000 to $1 million.
Redefines a constitutional provision that currently protects abortion rights.

Explanation: Provides raises for state workers.
Uses a portion of the state budget surplus for short-term property tax rebates.
“Debt-free in ‘23” bill that funds the pay down of some state bonds.
Creates an income tax credit for property tax relief.
Articulates a broad management framework for grizzlies if they are taken off the endangered species list.
Gives the attorney general and speaker of the House appointment power for the body that reviews judicial misconduct complaints.
categoryDescription: Changes to laws governing the Montana court system.

Explanation: Raises the bar for courts to issue preliminary injunctions and temporary restraining orders in legal proceedings.
categoryDescription: Changes to laws governing the Montana court system.

Explanation: Limits the types of patients who can be committed to the Montana State Hospital.
Advances new funding model for mental health and addiction treatment providers.
Adds legal requirements in child removal cases.
Codifies federal protections for Native American children, families and tribal nations in state law.
Prohibits gender-affirming medical and surgical care for transgender minors.
categoryDescription: Bills at the intersection of religious liberty, free speech and human rights.

Explanation: Allows medical providers to withhold services based on ethical, moral, or religious beliefs.
categoryDescription: Bills at the intersection of religious liberty, free speech and human rights.

Explanation: Bars drag performances in publicly funded schools and libraries.
categoryDescription: Bills at the intersection of religious liberty, free speech and human rights.

Explanation: Invests $60 million in establishing a statewide school health insurance trust.
Alters Montana obscenity laws so criminal penalties could apply to public school employees.
Lets some Montana kids enter kindergarten programs before age 5 to promote literacy.
Requires counties to conduct Election Day ballot counts without taking a break.
Lets counties add a local race to their routine post-election audit of statewide races to verify voting machine accuracy.
Puts $100 million into a highway fund to help the state access federal match dollars.
Comprehensive planning statute overhaul that would require large cities to allocate space to house population growth.
Puts $15 million into coal trust-backed loans to subsidizes price-restricted housing projects.
Puts $500 million of budget surplus to price-restricted housing efforts.
Prevents courts from granting notice-less temporary restraining orders against the state or other units of government.
categoryDescription: Changes to laws governing the Montana court system.

Explanation: Requires judges to recuse themselves from a case when parties or lawyers involved have donated a certain amount to their campaigns.
categoryDescription: Changes to laws governing the Montana court system.

Explanation: Broadens the Legislature’s subpoena and investigative powers.
Enhances reporting requirements for schools that receive IEFA funds.
Creates a charter school system under an autonomous state commission.
Creates a charter school system under the jurisdiction of existing school boards and state education officials.
Expands eligibility for student loan assistance for new teachers.
Expands eligibility for incentives that boost starting teacher pay.
Proscribes how public schools should teach financial literacy courses.
Requires counties to collect and retain digital records of ballots counted by vote tabulating machines.
Requires counties to routinely review absentee voter lists to verify address accuracy.
Redraws the districts used to elect the state utility regulation commission.
Would allow state regulators to pre-approve energy projects proposed by large monopoly utilities.
Provides for relocation or killing of bears involved in livestock conflicts if grizzlies are delisted.
Redirects revenue that currently goes toward wildlife habitat and public access programs.
Increases Medicaid provider rates to benchmark rates identified by a state-commissioned study.
Provides inflation adjustments for nursing homes and revises waiver programs for senior and long-term care.
Prohibits most second-trimester abortions by barring dilation and evacuation procedures.
Bans abortions based on gestational viability, presumed at 24 weeks.
Requires pre-authorization and increased documentation for Medicaid-eligible abortions.
Requires life-sustaining medical care for newborns, including those diagnosed with fatal health conditions.
Precludes legal recognition of transgender people and those with intersex conditions by defining 'sex' based on reproductive systems.
categoryDescription: Bills at the intersection of religious liberty, free speech and human rights.

Explanation: Submits a 2024 ballot measure that would create a constitutional right to hunt, trap and fish.
Expands the volume of well water available to large, multi-phase subdivisions outside of a water rights permitting process.
As amended, requires larger cities to allow duplexes on all home lots.
Requires larger cities to allow apartment-style housing in most commercial zones.
Boosts housing construction by putting $200 million toward infrastructure loans.
Puts $115 million into coal trust-backed loans to subsidize price-restricted housing projects.
As amended, bundles several housing investment proposals into a single bill.
Specifies that state environmental reviews can’t analyze greenhouse gas impacts.
Makes it harder to challenge projects under the Montana Environmental Policy Act.
Major infrastructure bill, generally funding state facility and university projects.
Allocates an additional $135 million for property and income tax rebates.
Allocates money for state prison facilities.
Transfers money into law enforcement pension systems and adjusts some policies.
Expands legislative authority over portions of the state Capitol and surrounding buildings.
Makes it easier for lawmakers to participate in litigation over legislation.
Raises the number of signatures non-major party candidates must gather to qualify for the ballot.
‘Jungle primary’ bill.
Proposes switching state supreme court justice selection from statewide elections to appointments made by the governor.
categoryDescription: Changes to laws governing the Montana court system.

Explanation: Proposes allowing the Legislature to overrule university system regents on free speech policy.
Proposes amendment barring use of political data while drawing political maps.
Removes language specifying that the state’s constitutional right to bear arms doesn’t permit concealed carry.
Expands child care subsidy program.
Allocates $300 million for expanding mental health infrastructure and services.
Requires expedited court hearings after the state removes children from their homes.
Combines all Montana elections on the same ballots in even-numbered years.
